<p><b>Mathematics</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academi=
c_discipline" title=3D"Academic discipline">field of study</a> that discove=
rs and organizes methods, theories, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Theorem" title=3D"Theorem">theorems</a> that are developed and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_proof" title=3D"Mathematica=
l proof">proved</a> for the needs of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Empirical_sciences" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Empirical sciences">e=
mpirical sciences</a> and mathematics itself. There are many areas of mathe=
matics, which include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theor=
y" title=3D"Number theory">number theory</a> (the study of numbers), <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">algebra</a> (=
the study of formulas and related structures), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry">geometry</a> (the study of shapes=
 and spaces that contain them), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
thematical_analysis" title=3D"Mathematical analysis">analysis</a> (the stud=
y of continuous changes), and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_=
theory" title=3D"Set theory">set theory</a> (presently used as a foundation=
 for all mathematics).
</p><p>Mathematics involves the description and manipulation of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_object" title=3D"Mathematical ob=
ject">abstract objects</a> that consist of either <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Abstraction_(mathematics)" title=3D"Abstraction (mathematic=
s)">abstractions</a> from nature or=E2=80=94in modern mathematics=E2=80=94p=
urely abstract entities that are stipulated to have certain properties, cal=
led <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom" title=3D"Axiom">axio=
ms</a></i>.  Mathematics uses pure <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Reason" title=3D"Reason">reason</a> to prove the properties of objects thr=
ough <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_proof" title=
=3D"Mathematical proof">proofs</a></i>, which consist of a succession of ap=
plications of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inference_rule" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inference rule">deductive rules</a> to already e=
stablished results. These results, called <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Theorem" title=3D"Theorem">theorems</a></i>, include previously =
proved theorems, axioms, and=E2=80=94in case of abstraction from nature=E2=
=80=94some basic properties that are considered true starting points of the=
 theory under consideration.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-1"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Mathematics is essential in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Natural_science" title=3D"Natural science">natural sciences</a>, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engineering">engi=
neering</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medicine" title=3D"Me=
dicine">medicine</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finance" tit=
le=3D"Finance">finance</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comput=
er_science" title=3D"Computer science">computer science</a>, and the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_sciences" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Social sciences">social sciences</a>. Although mathematics is exten=
sively used for modeling phenomena, the fundamental truths of mathematics a=
re independent of any scientific experimentation. Some areas of mathematics=
, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Sta=
tistics">statistics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_t=
heory" title=3D"Game theory">game theory</a>, are developed in close correl=
ation with their applications and are often grouped under <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Applied_mathematics" title=3D"Applied mathematics">=
applied mathematics</a>. Other areas are developed independently from any a=
pplication (and are therefore called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pure_mathematics" title=3D"Pure mathematics">pure mathematics</a>) but o=
ften later find practical applications.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPeterson=
198812_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
thematics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPeterson198812-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-wigner1960_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Mathematics#cite_note-wigner1960-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Historically, the concept of a proof and its associated <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_rigour" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Mathematical rigour">mathematical rigour</a> first appeared in <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Greek mathematics">Greek mathematics</a>, most notably in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a>'s <i>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Eucl=
id's Elements">Elements</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-4"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Since its beginning, mathematics was primarily divided into geometry and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic" title=3D"Arithmetic">a=
rithmetics</a> (the manipulation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Natural_number" title=3D"Natural number">natural numbers</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Fractions">fractions</a>) until the 16th and 17th centuries, when algebra<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Infinitesimal_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Infini=
tesimal calculus">infinitesimal calculus</a> were introduced as new fields.=
 Since then, the interaction between mathematical innovations and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_scientific_discoveries" title=
=3D"Timeline of scientific discoveries">scientific discoveries</a> has led =
to a correlated increase in the development of both.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#ci=
te_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> At the end of the 19th century, the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foundational_crisis_of_mathematics" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Foundational crisis of mathematics">foundational crisis of =
mathematics</a> led to the systematization of the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Axiomatic_method" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Axiomatic =
method">axiomatic method</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kleiner_1991_7-0" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-=
Kleiner_1991-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> which heralded a dramatic increase in the number=
 of mathematical areas and their fields of application. The contemporary <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_Subject_Classification" =
title=3D"Mathematics Subject Classification">Mathematics Subject Classifica=
tion</a> lists more than sixty first-level areas of mathematics.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-MSC_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics#cite_note-MSC-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-MSC2020_9-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#c=
ite_note-MSC2020-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"toclimit-3"><meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc"></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Areas_of_mathematics">Areas=
 of mathematics</h2></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Branches_of_mathematics"></span>
Before the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renaissance" title=3D"R=
enaissance">Renaissance</a>, mathematics was divided into two main areas: <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic" title=3D"Arithmetic">ar=
ithmetic</a>, regarding the manipulation of numbers, and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry">geometry</a>, regarding=
 the study of shapes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some ty=
pes of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudoscience" title=3D"Pse=
udoscience">pseudoscience</a>, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Numerology" title=3D"Numerology">numerology</a> and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astrology" title=3D"Astrology">astrology</a>, were n=
ot then clearly distinguished from mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_n=
ote-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>During the Renaissance, two more areas appeared. <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_notation" title=3D"Mathematical notation=
">Mathematical notation</a> led to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">algebra</a> which, roughly speaking, consists o=
f the study and the manipulation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Formula" title=3D"Formula">formulas</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">Calculus</a>, consisting of the two s=
ubfields <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_calculus"=
 title=3D"Differential calculus">differential calculus</a></i> and <i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Integral calculus">integral calculus</a></i>, is the study of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_functions" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Continuous functions">continuous functions</a>, which mode=
l the typically <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nonlinear_system" =
title=3D"Nonlinear system">nonlinear relationships</a> between varying quan=
tities, as represented by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable=
_(mathematics)" title=3D"Variable (mathematics)">variables</a>. This divisi=
on into four main areas=E2=80=94arithmetic, geometry, algebra, and calculus=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=E2=80=94endured until the e=
nd of the 19th century. Areas such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Celestial_mechanics" title=3D"Celestial mechanics">celestial mechanics<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid_mechanics" title=3D"=
Solid mechanics">solid mechanics</a> were then studied by mathematicians, b=
ut now are considered as belonging to physics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_no=
te-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> The subject of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Combinatorics" title=3D"Combinatorics">combinatorics</a> has been studied f=
or much of recorded history, yet did not become a separate branch of mathem=
atics until the 17th century.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-14"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>At the end of the 19th century, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Foundational_crisis_in_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Foundational crisis in mathematics">foundational crisis in mathematics</a>=
 and the resulting systematization of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Axiomatic_method" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Axiomatic method">=
axiomatic method</a> led to an explosion of new areas of mathematics.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Warner_2013_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Warner_2013-15"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Kleiner_1991_7-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Kleiner_1991-7"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The 2020 =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_Subject_Classification=
" title=3D"Mathematics Subject Classification">Mathematics Subject Classifi=
cation</a> contains no less than <em>sixty-three</em> first-level areas.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-MSC2020_9-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-MSC2020-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some of these a=
reas correspond to the older division, as is true regarding <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Number theory">number the=
ory</a> (the modern name for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Highe=
r_arithmetic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Higher arithmetic">higher arit=
hmetic</a>) and geometry. Several other first-level areas have "geometry" i=
n their names or are otherwise commonly considered part of geometry. Algebr=
a and calculus do not appear as first-level areas but are respectively spli=
t into several first-level areas. Other first-level areas emerged during th=
e 20th century or had not previously been considered as mathematics, such a=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_logic" title=3D"Mat=
hematical logic">mathematical logic</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Foundations_of_mathematics" title=3D"Foundations of mathematics">=
foundations</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MSC_8-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-MSC-8"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Number_theory">Number theor=
y</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=
=3D"Number theory">Number theory</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
