ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-16"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Number theory dates back to ancient <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Babylonian_mathematics" title=3D"Babylonian mathematics">Babylon</a> and=
 probably <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_China" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Ancient China">China</a>. Two prominent early number =
theorists were <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Eu=
clid">Euclid</a> of ancient Greece and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Diophantus" title=3D"Diophantus">Diophantus</a> of Alexandria.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Mathematics#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The modern study of number theory =
in its abstract form is largely attributed to <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Pierre_de_Fermat" title=3D"Pierre de Fermat">Pierre de Fermat</=
a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Euler" title=3D"Le=
onhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a>. The field came to full fruition with the =
contributions of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrien-Marie_Lege=
ndre" title=3D"Adrien-Marie Legendre">Adrien-Marie Legendre</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Fried=
rich Gauss">Carl Friedrich Gauss</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-18"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p>Many easily stated number problems have solutions that require sophi=
sticated methods, often from across mathematics. A prominent example is <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem" title=3D"Fer=
mat's Last Theorem">Fermat's Last Theorem</a>. This conjecture was stated i=
n 1637 by Pierre de Fermat, but it <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Wiles%27s_proof_of_Fermat%27s_Last_Theorem" title=3D"Wiles's proof of Ferm=
at's Last Theorem">was proved</a> only in 1994 by <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Wiles" title=3D"Andrew Wiles">Andrew Wiles</a>, who =
used tools including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scheme_theory=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Scheme theory">scheme theory</a> from <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_geometry" title=3D"Algebraic=
 geometry">algebraic geometry</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Category_theory" title=3D"Category theory">category theory</a>, and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homological_algebra" title=3D"Homologica=
l algebra">homological algebra</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-19"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> Another example is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldbac=
h%27s_conjecture" title=3D"Goldbach's conjecture">Goldbach's conjecture</a>=
, which asserts that every even integer greater than 2 is the sum of two <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number"=
>prime numbers</a>. Stated in 1742 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Christian_Goldbach" title=3D"Christian Goldbach">Christian Goldbach</a>=
, it remains unproven despite considerable effort.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cit=
e_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Number theory includes several subareas, including <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_number_theory" title=3D"Analytic number th=
eory">analytic number theory</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Algebraic_number_theory" title=3D"Algebraic number theory">algebraic number=
 theory</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry_of_numbers" =
title=3D"Geometry of numbers">geometry of numbers</a> (method oriented), <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophantine_analysis" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Diophantine analysis">Diophantine analysis</a>, and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcendence_theory" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Transcendence theory">transcendence theory</a> (problem orient=
ed).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MSC_8-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-MSC-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Geometry">Geometry</h3></di=
v>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"G=
eometry">Geometry</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Triangles_(spherical_geometry).jpg" class=3D"=
mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/com=
mons/thumb/9/97/Triangles_%28spherical_geometry%29.jpg/250px-Triangles_%28s=
pherical_geometry%29.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"206" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2489" data-file-height=3D"2048"=
></a><figcaption>On the surface of a sphere, Euclidean geometry only applie=
s as a local approximation. For larger scales the sum of the angles of a tr=
iangle is not equal to 180=C2=B0.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Geometry is one of the oldest branches of mathematics. It started with e=
mpirical recipes concerning shapes, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Line_(geometry)" title=3D"Line (geometry)">lines</a>, <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angle" title=3D"Angle">angles</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circle" title=3D"Circle">circles</a>, whi=
ch were developed mainly for the needs of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Surveying" title=3D"Surveying">surveying</a> and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Architecture" title=3D"Architecture">architecture</a=
>, but has since blossomed out into many other subfields.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-Straume_2014_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Straume_2014-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A fundamental innovation was the ancient Greeks' introduction of the=
 concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_proof" ti=
tle=3D"Mathematical proof">proofs</a>, which require that every assertion m=
ust be <i>proved</i>. For example, it is not sufficient to verify by <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measurement" title=3D"Measurement">measu=
rement</a> that, say, two lengths are equal; their equality must be proven =
via reasoning from previously accepted results (<a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Theorem" title=3D"Theorem">theorems</a>) and a few basic stat=
ements. The basic statements are not subject to proof because they are self=
-evident (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Postulate" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Postulate">postulates</a>), or are part of the definition=
 of the subject of study (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiom" t=
itle=3D"Axiom">axioms</a>). This principle, foundational for all mathematic=
s, was first elaborated for geometry, and was systematized by <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a> around 300 =
BC in his book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_Eleme=
nts" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Elements</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cit=
e_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The resulting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_geo=
metry" title=3D"Euclidean geometry">Euclidean geometry</a> is the study of =
shapes and their arrangements <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stra=
ightedge_and_compass_construction" title=3D"Straightedge and compass constr=
uction">constructed</a> from lines, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Plane_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plane (geometry)">planes=
</a> and circles in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_=
plane" title=3D"Euclidean plane">Euclidean plane</a> (<a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_geometry" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plane ge=
ometry">plane geometry</a>) and the three-dimensional <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_space" title=3D"Euclidean space">Euclidean sp=
ace</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>b<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-S=
traume_2014_21-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics#cite_note-Straume_2014-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Euclidean geometry was developed without change of methods or scope =
until the 17th century, when <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C=
3%A9_Descartes" title=3D"Ren=C3=A9 Descartes">Ren=C3=A9 Descartes</a> intro=
duced what is now called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian=
_coordinates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cartesian coordinates">Cartesi=
an coordinates</a>. This constituted a major <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Paradigm_shift" title=3D"Paradigm shift">change of paradigm</a>:=
 Instead of defining <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" =
title=3D"Real number">real numbers</a> as lengths of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_segments" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Line segme=
nts">line segments</a> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number=
_line" title=3D"Number line">number line</a>), it allowed the representatio=
n of points using their <i>coordinates</i>, which are numbers. Algebra (and=
 later, calculus) can thus be used to solve geometrical problems. Geometry =
was split into two new subfields: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Synthetic_geometry" title=3D"Synthetic geometry">synthetic geometry</a>, wh=
ich uses purely geometrical methods, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Analytic_geometry" title=3D"Analytic geometry">analytic geometry</a>=
, which uses coordinates systemically.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-25"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>Analytic geometry allows the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Curve" title=3D"Curve">curves</a> unrelated to circles and lines=
. Such curves can be defined as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Graph_of_a_function" title=3D"Graph of a function">graph of functions</a>=
, the study of which led to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differ=
ential_geometry" title=3D"Differential geometry">differential geometry</a>.=
 They can also be defined as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impli=
cit_equation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Implicit equation">implicit eq=
uations</a>, often <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_equa=
tion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polynomial equation">polynomial equati=
ons</a> (which spawned <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_g=
eometry" title=3D"Algebraic geometry">algebraic geometry</a>). Analytic geo=
metry also makes it possible to consider Euclidean spaces of higher than th=
ree dimensions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Straume_2014_21-2" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Straume_2014-=
21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 19th century, mathematicians discovered <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-Euclidean_geometries" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Non-Euclidean geometries">non-Euclidean geometries</a>, which do not fo=
llow the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_postulate" title=
=3D"Parallel postulate">parallel postulate</a>. By questioning that postula=
te's truth, this discovery has been viewed as joining <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell%27s_paradox" title=3D"Russell's paradox">Russel=
l's paradox</a> in revealing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
oundational_crisis_of_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Foundatio=
nal crisis of mathematics">foundational crisis of mathematics</a>. This asp=
ect of the crisis was solved by systematizing the axiomatic method, and ado=
pting that the truth of the chosen axioms is not a mathematical problem.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kleiner_199=
1_7-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathema=
tics#cite_note-Kleiner_1991-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In turn, the axiomatic method all=
ows for the study of various geometries obtained either by changing the axi=
oms or by considering properties that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Invariant_(mathematics)" title=3D"Invariant (mathematics)">do not chang=
e</a> under specific transformations of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Space_(mathematics)" title=3D"Space (mathematics)">space</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Today's subareas of geometry include:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MSC_8-3" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite=
_note-MSC-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projective_geometry" title=
=3D"Projective geometry">Projective geometry</a>, introduced in the 16th ce=
ntury by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girard_Desargues" title=
=3D"Girard Desargues">Girard Desargues</a>, extends Euclidean geometry by a=
dding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Points_at_infinity" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Points at infinity">points at infinity</a> at which =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_lines" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Parallel lines">parallel lines</a> intersect. This simplifies =
many aspects of classical geometry by unifying the treatments for intersect=
ing and parallel lines.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affine_geometry" title=3D"Affi=
ne geometry">Affine geometry</a>, the study of properties relative to <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallel_(geometry)" title=3D"Parallel =
(geometry)">parallelism</a> and independent from the concept of length.</li=
>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_geometry" title=
=3D"Differential geometry">Differential geometry</a>, the study of curves, =
surfaces, and their generalizations, which are defined using <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differentiable_function" title=3D"Differentiable=
 function">differentiable functions</a>.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manifold_theory" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Manifold theory">Manifold theory</a>, the study of shapes=
 that are not necessarily embedded in a larger space.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riemannian_geometry" title=3D"=
Riemannian geometry">Riemannian geometry</a>, the study of distance propert=
ies in curved spaces.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_geometry" title=3D"A=
lgebraic geometry">Algebraic geometry</a>, the study of curves, surfaces, a=
nd their generalizations, which are defined using <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynomials</a>.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topology" title=3D"Topology">T=
opology</a>, the study of properties that are kept under <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_deformation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Continuous deformation">continuous deformations</a>.
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_topology" title=
=3D"Algebraic topology">Algebraic topology</a>, the use in topology of alge=
braic methods, mainly <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homological_=
algebra" title=3D"Homological algebra">homological algebra</a>.</li></ul></=
li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_geometry" title=3D"Di=
screte geometry">Discrete geometry</a>, the study of finite configurations =
in geometry.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_geometry" title=3D"Conv=
ex geometry">Convex geometry</a>, the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Convex_set" title=3D"Convex set">convex sets</a>, which takes =
its importance from its applications in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Convex_optimization" title=3D"Convex optimization">optimization</a>.<=
/li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_geometry" title=3D"Com=
plex geometry">Complex geometry</a>, the geometry obtained by replacing rea=
l numbers with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" tit=
le=3D"Complex number">complex numbers</a>.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Algebra">Algebra</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Al=
gebra">Algebra</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size skin-invert-image" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Quadratic_formula.svg" clas=
s=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"refer to caption" src=3D"https://uplo=
ad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Quadratic_formula.svg/250px-Q=
uadratic_formula.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"77" cl=
ass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"402" data-file-height=3D"124"></=
a><figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_formul=
a" title=3D"Quadratic formula">quadratic formula</a>, which concisely expre=
sses the solutions of all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrati=
c_equation" title=3D"Quadratic equation">quadratic equations</a></figcaptio=
n></figure>  <figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Rubik%27s_cube.svg" class=3D"mw-=
file-description"><img alt=3D"A shuffled 3x3 rubik's cube" src=3D"https://u=
pload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Rubik%27s_cube.svg/250px-R=
ubik%27s_cube.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"260" clas=
s=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"480" data-file-height=3D"500"></a>=
<figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rubik%27s_Cube_gro=
up" title=3D"Rubik's Cube group">Rubik's Cube group</a> is a concrete appli=
cation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_theory" title=3D"G=
roup theory">group theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-28"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p></figcaption></figure>
<p>Algebra is the art of manipulating <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Equation" title=3D"Equation">equations</a> and formulas. <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diophantus" title=3D"Diophantus">Diophantus</a> =
(3rd century) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Khwarizmi" ti=
tle=3D"Al-Khwarizmi">al-Khwarizmi</a> (9th century) were the two main precu=
rsors of algebra.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKleiner2007&quot;History_of_Classical_Algebra&quot;_pp._3=
=E2=80=935_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Mathematics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKleiner2007%22History_of_Classical_Algebra=
%22_pp._3%E2%80%935-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Diophantus solved some equations invol=
ving unknown natural numbers by deducing new relations until he obtained th=
e solution.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Al-Khwarizmi int=
roduced systematic methods for transforming equations, such as moving a ter=
m from one side of an equation into the other side.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#ci=
te_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> The term <i>algebra</i> is derived from the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arabic" title=3D"Arabic">Arabic</a> word =
<i>al-jabr</i> meaning 'the reunion of broken parts' that he used for namin=
g one of these methods in the title of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/The_Compendious_Book_on_Calculation_by_Completion_and_Balancing" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"The Compendious Book on Calculation by Completion=
 and Balancing">his main treatise</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-33"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Algebra became an area in its own right only with <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fran%C3%A7ois_Vi%C3%A8te" title=3D"Fran=C3=A7ois Vi=
=C3=A8te">Fran=C3=A7ois Vi=C3=A8te</a> (1540=E2=80=931603), who introduced =
the use of variables for representing unknown or unspecified numbers.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Variables allow mathematicians to=
 describe the operations that have to be done on the numbers represented us=
ing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_formulas" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematical formulas">mathematical formulas</a>.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Until the 19th century, algebra consisted mainly of the study of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_equation" title=3D"Linear equa=
tion">linear equations</a> (presently <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D"Linear algebra">linear algebra</a></i>), an=
d polynomial equations in a single <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Unknown_(algebra)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Unknown (algebra)">unkno=
wn</a>, which were called <i>algebraic equations</i> (a term still in use, =
although it may be ambiguous). During the 19th century, mathematicians bega=
n to use variables to represent things other than numbers (such as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (ma=
thematics)">matrices</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_=
arithmetic" title=3D"Modular arithmetic">modular integers</a>, and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_transformation" title=3D"Geomet=
ric transformation">geometric transformations</a>), on which generalization=
s of arithmetic operations are often valid.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKlei=
ner2007&quot;History_of_Linear_Algebra&quot;_pp._79=E2=80=93101_37-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_no=
te-FOOTNOTEKleiner2007%22History_of_Linear_Algebra%22_pp._79%E2%80%93101-37=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> The concept of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algeb=
raic_structure" title=3D"Algebraic structure">algebraic structure</a> addre=
sses this, consisting of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(ma=
thematics)" title=3D"Set (mathematics)">set</a> whose elements are unspecif=
ied, of operations acting on the elements of the set, and rules that these =
operations must follow. The scope of algebra thus grew to include the study=
 of algebraic structures. This object of algebra was called <i>modern algeb=
ra</i> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abstract_algebra" title=
=3D"Abstract algebra">abstract algebra</a>, as established by the influence=
 and works of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emmy_Noether" title=
=3D"Emmy Noether">Emmy Noether</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-38"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
and popularized by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Van_der_Waerden=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Van der Waerden">Van der Waerden</a>'s boo=
k <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moderne_Algebra" title=3D"Mod=
erne Algebra">Moderne Algebra</a></i>.
</p><p>Some types of algebraic structures have useful and often fundamental=
 properties, in many areas of mathematics. Their study became autonomous pa=
rts of algebra, and include:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MSC_8-4" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-MSC-8"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_theory" title=3D"Gro=
up theory">group theory</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_(mathematics)" title=3D"=
Field (mathematics)">field theory</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_space" title=3D"Vector =
space">vector spaces</a>, whose study is essentially the same as <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D"Linear algebra">lin=
ear algebra</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_theory" title=3D"Ring the=
ory">ring theory</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commutative_algebra" title=3D"=
Commutative algebra">commutative algebra</a>, which is the study of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commutative_ring" title=3D"Commutative ri=
ng">commutative rings</a>, includes the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynomials</a>, and is a f=
oundational part of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_geom=
etry" title=3D"Algebraic geometry">algebraic geometry</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homological_algebra" title=3D"=
Homological algebra">homological algebra</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_algebra" title=3D"Lie alge=
bra">Lie algebra</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lie_group=
" title=3D"Lie group">Lie group</a> theory</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra" title=3D"Bool=
ean algebra">Boolean algebra</a>, which is widely used for the study of the=
 logical structure of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer" ti=
tle=3D"Computer">computers</a></li></ul>
<p>The study of types of algebraic structures as <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_object" title=3D"Mathematical object">mathemati=
cal objects</a> is the purpose of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Universal_algebra" title=3D"Universal algebra">universal algebra</a> and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category_theory" title=3D"Category t=
heory">category theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-39"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The latter applies to every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathe=
matical_structure" title=3D"Mathematical structure">mathematical structure<=
/a> (not only algebraic ones). At its origin, it was introduced, together w=
ith homological algebra for allowing the algebraic study of non-algebraic o=
bjects such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topological_space" =
title=3D"Topological space">topological spaces</a>; this particular area of=
 application is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_t=
opology" title=3D"Algebraic topology">algebraic topology</a>.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Math=
ematics#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Calculus_and_analysis">Calc=
ulus and analysis</h3></div>
