Calculus">Calculus</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathema=
tical_analysis" title=3D"Mathematical analysis">Mathematical analysis</a></=
div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Cauchy_sequence_illustration.svg" class=3D"mw=
-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commo=
ns/thumb/6/62/Cauchy_sequence_illustration.svg/250px-Cauchy_sequence_illust=
ration.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"139" class=3D"mw=
-file-element" data-file-width=3D"305" data-file-height=3D"170"></a><figcap=
tion>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cauchy_sequence" title=3D"C=
auchy sequence">Cauchy sequence</a> consists of elements such that all subs=
equent terms of a term become arbitrarily close to each other as the sequen=
ce progresses (from left to right).</figcaption></figure>
<p>Calculus, formerly called infinitesimal calculus, was introduced indepen=
dently and simultaneously by 17th-century mathematicians <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton">Newton</a> and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leibniz" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Leibniz">Leibniz</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-41"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 It is fundamentally the study of the relationship between variables that d=
epend continuously on each other. Calculus was expanded in the 18th century=
 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Euler">Euler</a> with the introduction of the concept of a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function=
 (mathematics)">function</a> and many other results.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#c=
ite_note-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> Presently, "calculus" refers mainly to the element=
ary part of this theory, and "analysis" is commonly used for advanced parts=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Analysis is further subdivided into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Real_analysis" title=3D"Real analysis">real analysis</a>, where va=
riables represent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" tit=
le=3D"Real number">real numbers</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Complex_analysis" title=3D"Complex analysis">complex analysis</a>, w=
here variables represent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_n=
umber" title=3D"Complex number">complex numbers</a>. Analysis includes many=
 subareas shared by other areas of mathematics which include:<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-MSC_8-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Mathematics#cite_note-MSC-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariable_calculus" ti=
tle=3D"Multivariable calculus">Multivariable calculus</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_analysis" title=3D"=
Functional analysis">Functional analysis</a>, where variables represent var=
ying functions</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integration_(mathematics)" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Integration (mathematics)">Integration</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measure_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Measure theory">measure theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Potential_theory" title=3D"Potential theory">potential theor=
y</a>, all strongly related with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
robability_theory" title=3D"Probability theory">probability theory</a> on a=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuum_(set_theory)" title=3D"=
Continuum (set theory)">continuum</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ordinary_differential_equation=
" title=3D"Ordinary differential equation">Ordinary differential equations<=
/a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_differential_equation"=
 title=3D"Partial differential equation">Partial differential equations</a>=
</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_analysis" title=3D"N=
umerical analysis">Numerical analysis</a>, mainly devoted to the computatio=
n on computers of solutions of ordinary and partial differential equations =
that arise in many applications</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Discrete_mathematics">Discr=
ete mathematics</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_mathematics=
" title=3D"Discrete mathematics">Discrete mathematics</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right skin-invert-image" typeof=
=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Markovkate=
_01.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia=
.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/Markovkate_01.svg/250px-Markovkate_01.svg=
.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" class=3D"mw-file-elem=
ent" data-file-width=3D"563" data-file-height=3D"563"></a><figcaption>A dia=
gram representing a two-state <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark=
ov_chain" title=3D"Markov chain">Markov chain</a>. The states are represent=
ed by 'A' and 'E'. The numbers are the probability of flipping the state.</=
figcaption></figure>
<p>Discrete mathematics, broadly speaking, is the study of individual, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Countable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Countable">countable</a> mathematical objects. An example is the set of=
 all integers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Because the o=
bjects of study here are discrete, the methods of calculus and mathematical=
 analysis do not directly apply.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-45"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>c<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm"=
>Algorithms</a>=E2=80=94especially their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Implementation" title=3D"Implementation">implementation</a> and <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_complexity" title=3D"Com=
putational complexity">computational complexity</a>=E2=80=94play a major ro=
le in discrete mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-46"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four_color_theorem" tit=
le=3D"Four color theorem">four color theorem</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Kepler_conjecture" title=3D"Kepler conjecture">optimal s=
phere packing</a> were two major problems of discrete mathematics solved in=
 the second half of the 20th century.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-47"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P_versus_NP_problem"=
 title=3D"P versus NP problem">P versus NP problem</a>, which remains open =
to this day, is also important for discrete mathematics, since its solution=
 would potentially impact a large number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Computationally_expensive" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Computa=
tionally expensive">computationally difficult</a> problems.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathem=
atics#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Discrete mathematics includes:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MSC_8-6" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-M=
SC-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorics" title=3D"Co=
mbinatorics">Combinatorics</a>, the art of enumerating mathematical objects=
 that satisfy some given constraints. Originally, these objects were elemen=
ts or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subset" title=3D"Subset">sub=
sets</a> of a given <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(mathemati=
cs)" title=3D"Set (mathematics)">set</a>; this has been extended to various=
 objects, which establishes a strong link between combinatorics and other p=
arts of discrete mathematics. For example, discrete geometry includes count=
ing configurations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_sh=
ape" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Geometric shape">geometric shapes</a>.<=
/li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_theory" title=3D"Graph t=
heory">Graph theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperg=
raph" title=3D"Hypergraph">hypergraphs</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coding_theory" title=3D"Coding=
 theory">Coding theory</a>, including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Error_correcting_code" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Error correcting =
code">error correcting codes</a> and a part of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Cryptography" title=3D"Cryptography">cryptography</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matroid" title=3D"Matroid">Mat=
roid</a> theory</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_geometry" title=3D"Di=
screte geometry">Discrete geometry</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_probability_distribut=
ion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Discrete probability distribution">Disc=
rete probability distributions</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory" title=3D"Game the=
ory">Game theory</a> (although <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Con=
tinuous_game" title=3D"Continuous game">continuous games</a> are also studi=
ed, most common games, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Che=
ss" title=3D"Chess">chess</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Poker" title=3D"Poker">poker</a> are discrete)</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_optimization" title=
=3D"Discrete optimization">Discrete optimization</a>, including <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorial_optimization" title=3D"Combinat=
orial optimization">combinatorial optimization</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_programming" title=3D"Integer programming">intege=
r programming</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constraint_prog=
ramming" title=3D"Constraint programming">constraint programming</a></li></=
ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mathematical_logic_and_set_=
theory">Mathematical logic and set theory</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_logic"=
 title=3D"Mathematical logic">Mathematical logic</a> and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory" title=3D"Set theory">Set theory</a></div=
>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Venn_A_intersect_B.svg" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img alt=3D"A blue and pink circle and their intersection labeled"=
 src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/Venn_A_in=
tersect_B.svg/250px-Venn_A_intersect_B.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"250" height=3D"179" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"350" data=
-file-height=3D"250"></a><figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Venn_diagram" title=3D"Venn diagram">Venn diagram</a> is a commonly =
used method to illustrate the relations between sets.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The two subjects of mathematical logic and set theory have belonged to m=
athematics since the end of the 19th century.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_no=
te-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Before th=
is period, sets were not considered to be mathematical objects, and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic" title=3D"Logic">logic</a>, althoug=
h used for mathematical proofs, belonged to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Philosophy" title=3D"Philosophy">philosophy</a> and was not speci=
fically studied by mathematicians.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-51"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p><p>Before <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georg_Cantor" title=
=3D"Georg Cantor">Cantor</a>'s study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Infinite_set" title=3D"Infinite set">infinite sets</a>, mathematician=
s were reluctant to consider <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Actua=
lly_infinite" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Actually infinite">actually in=
finite</a> collections, and considered <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Infinity" title=3D"Infinity">infinity</a> to be the result of endless =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enumeration" title=3D"Enumeration"=
>enumeration</a>. Cantor's work offended many mathematicians not only by co=
nsidering actually infinite sets<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-52"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> but by showing that this implies different sizes of infinity, per <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cantor%27s_diagonal_argument" title=3D=
"Cantor's diagonal argument">Cantor's diagonal argument</a>. This led to th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Controversy_over_Cantor%27s_theo=
ry" title=3D"Controversy over Cantor's theory">controversy over Cantor's se=
t theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the same pe=
riod, various areas of mathematics concluded the former intuitive definitio=
ns of the basic mathematical objects were insufficient for ensuring <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_rigour" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Mathematical rigour">mathematical rigour</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathemati=
cs#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>This became the foundational crisis of mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathema=
tics#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It was eventually solved in mainstream mathe=
matics by systematizing the axiomatic method inside a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zermelo%E2%80%93Fraenkel_set_theory" title=3D"Zermelo=
=E2=80=93Fraenkel set theory">formalized set theory</a>. Roughly speaking, =
each mathematical object is defined by the set of all similar objects and t=
he properties that these objects must have.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Warner_2013_=
15-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathemat=
ics#cite_note-Warner_2013-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, in <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peano_arithmetic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pe=
ano arithmetic">Peano arithmetic</a>, the natural numbers are defined by "z=
ero is a number", "each number has a unique successor", "each number but ze=
ro has a unique predecessor", and some rules of reasoning.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-56" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathema=
tics#cite_note-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Mathematical_abstraction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematical abs=
traction">mathematical abstraction</a> from reality is embodied in the mode=
rn philosophy of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formalism_(philos=
ophy_of_mathematics)" title=3D"Formalism (philosophy of mathematics)">forma=
lism</a>, as founded by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Hilb=
ert" title=3D"David Hilbert">David Hilbert</a> around 1910.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Snapper_57-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics#cite_note-Snapper-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The "nature" of the objects defined this way is a philosophical prob=
lem that mathematicians leave to philosophers, even if many mathematicians =
have opinions on this nature, and use their opinion=E2=80=94sometimes calle=
d "intuition"=E2=80=94to guide their study and proofs. The approach allows =
considering "logics" (that is, sets of allowed deducing rules), theorems, p=
roofs, etc. as mathematical objects, and to prove theorems about them. For =
example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G%C3%B6del%27s_incomplete=
ness_theorems" title=3D"G=C3=B6del's incompleteness theorems">G=C3=B6del's =
incompleteness theorems</a> assert, roughly speaking that, in every <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consistent" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Consistent">consistent</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/For=
mal_system" title=3D"Formal system">formal system</a> that contains the nat=
ural numbers, there are theorems that are true (that is provable in a stron=
ger system), but not provable inside the system.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Raatika=
inen_2005_58-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Mathematics#cite_note-Raatikainen_2005-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This approach to t=
he foundations of mathematics was challenged during the first half of the 2=
0th century by mathematicians led by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/L._E._J._Brouwer" title=3D"L. E. J. Brouwer">Brouwer</a>, who promoted <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intuitionistic_logic" title=3D"Intu=
itionistic logic">intuitionistic logic</a> (which explicitly lacks the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_excluded_middle" title=3D"Law o=
f excluded middle">law of excluded middle</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_n=
ote-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>These problems and debates led to a wide expansion of mathematical l=
ogic, with subareas such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Model_=
theory" title=3D"Model theory">model theory</a> (modeling some logical theo=
ries inside other theories), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proof=
_theory" title=3D"Proof theory">proof theory</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Type_theory" title=3D"Type theory">type theory</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computability_theory" title=3D"Computabil=
ity theory">computability theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Computational_complexity_theory" title=3D"Computational complexity t=
heory">computational complexity theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MSC_8-7" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_=
note-MSC-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> Although these aspects of mathematical logic were in=
troduced before the rise of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comput=
er" title=3D"Computer">computers</a>, their use in <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Compiler" title=3D"Compiler">compiler</a> design, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formal_verification" title=3D"Formal veri=
fication">formal verification</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Program_analysis" title=3D"Program analysis">program analysis</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proof_assistant" title=3D"Proof assistant=
">proof assistants</a> and other aspects of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D"Computer science">computer science</a>=
, contributed in turn to the expansion of these logical theories.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Mathematics#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Statistics_and_other_decisi=
on_sciences">Statistics and other decision sciences</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=
=3D"Statistics">Statistics</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Probability_theory" title=3D"Probability theory">Probability theory</a></d=
iv>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right skin-invert-image" typeof=
=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Illustrati=
onCentralTheorem.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upl=
oad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/IllustrationCentralTheorem.p=
ng/500px-IllustrationCentralTheorem.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"380" h=
eight=3D"160" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2771" data-file-=
height=3D"1166"></a><figcaption>Whatever the form of a random population <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"P=
robability distribution">distribution</a> (=CE=BC), the sampling <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean" title=3D"Mean">mean</a> (x=CC=84) tend=
s to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_distribution" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gaussian distribution">Gaussian distribution</a>=
 and its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variance" title=3D"Varian=
ce">variance</a> (=CF=83) is given by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Central_limit_theorem" title=3D"Central limit theorem">central limi=
t theorem</a> of probability theory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-62"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>The field of statistics is a mathematical application that is employed f=
or the collection and processing of data samples, using procedures based on=
 mathematical methods such as, and especially, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D"Probability theory">probability t=
heory</a>. Statisticians generate data with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Random_sampling" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Random sampling">=
random sampling</a> or randomized <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Design_of_experiments" title=3D"Design of experiments">experiments</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_theory" title=
=3D"Statistical theory">Statistical theory</a> studies <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_decision_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Statistical decision theory">decision problems</a> such as minimizing=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Risk" title=3D"Risk">risk</a>=
 (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expected_loss" title=3D"Expected=
 loss">expected loss</a>) of a statistical action, such as using a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_method" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Statistical method">procedure</a> in, for example, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parameter_estimation" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Parameter estimation">parameter estimation</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypothesis_testing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hypot=
hesis testing">hypothesis testing</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Selection_algorithm" title=3D"Selection algorithm">selecting the b=
est</a>. In these traditional areas of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Mathematical_statistics" title=3D"Mathematical statistics">mathematica=
l statistics</a>, a statistical-decision problem is formulated by minimizin=
g an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Objective_function" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Objective function">objective function</a>, like expe=
cted loss or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cost" title=3D"Cost">=
cost</a>, under specific constraints. For example, designing a survey often=
 involves minimizing the cost of estimating a population mean with a given =
level of confidence.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-RaoOpt_64-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-RaoOpt-64"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> Because of its use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opt=
imization" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Optimization">optimization</a>, t=
he mathematical theory of statistics overlaps with other <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision_science" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dec=
ision science">decision sciences</a>, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Operations_research" title=3D"Operations research">operations r=
esearch</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_theory" title=
=3D"Control theory">control theory</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mathematical_economics" title=3D"Mathematical economics">mathemat=
ical economics</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWhittle199410=E2=80=9311,_14=
=E2=80=9318_65-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWhittle199410%E2%80%9311,_14%E2%80%9318-6=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Computational_mathematics">=
Computational mathematics</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_mathem=
atics" title=3D"Computational mathematics">Computational mathematics</a></d=
iv>
<p>Computational mathematics is the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mathematical_problem" title=3D"Mathematical problem">mathematica=
l problems</a> that are typically too large for human, numerical capacity.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-66"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-67" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_no=
te-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Part of computational mathematics involves <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_analysis" title=3D"Numerical analysis=
">numerical analysis</a>, which is the study of methods for problems in <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Analysis (mathematics)">analysis</a> using <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_analysis" title=3D"Functional analysi=
s">functional analysis</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/App=
roximation_theory" title=3D"Approximation theory">approximation theory</a>.=
 Numerical analysis broadly includes the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Approximation" title=3D"Approximation">approximation</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discretization" title=3D"Discret=
ization">discretization</a>, with special focus on <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Rounding_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rounding er=
ror">rounding errors</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-68" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-68"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Nu=
merical analysis and, more broadly, scientific computing, also study non-an=
alytic topics of mathematical science, especially algorithmic-<a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_linear_algebra" title=3D"Numerical li=
near algebra">matrix</a>-and-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph=
_theory" title=3D"Graph theory">graph theory</a>. Other areas of computatio=
nal mathematics include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_a=
lgebra" title=3D"Computer algebra">computer algebra</a> and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbolic_computation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Symbolic computation">symbolic computation</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MSC_=
8-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathemati=
cs#cite_note-MSC-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_mathemati=
cs" title=3D"History of mathematics">History of mathematics</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h3></=
div>
<p>The word <i>mathematics</i> comes from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title=3D"Ancient Greek">Ancient Greek</a> word <=
i>m=C3=A1th=C4=93ma</i> (<i><span title=3D"Ancient Greek-language text"><sp=
an lang=3D"grc"><span lang=3D"en"><a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki=
/%CE%BC%CE%AC%CE%B8%CE%B7%CE%BC%CE%B1#English" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wik=
t:=CE=BC=CE=AC=CE=B8=CE=B7=CE=BC=CE=B1">=CE=BC=CE=AC=CE=B8=CE=B7=CE=BC=CE=
=B1</a></span></span></span></i>), meaning <span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</sp=
an><span class=3D"gloss-text">something learned, knowledge, mathematics</sp=
an><span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span>, and the derived expression <i>math=
=C4=93matik=E1=B8=97 t=C3=A9khn=C4=93</i> (<span title=3D"Ancient Greek (to=
 1453)-language text"><span lang=3D"grc">=CE=BC=CE=B1=CE=B8=CE=B7=CE=BC=CE=
=B1=CF=84=CE=B9=CE=BA=E1=BD=B4 =CF=84=CE=AD=CF=87=CE=BD=CE=B7</span></span>=
), meaning <span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span><span class=3D"gloss-text">ma=
thematical science</span><span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span>. It entered th=
e English language during the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Late=
_Middle_English" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Late Middle English">Late M=
iddle English</a> period through French and Latin.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cit=
e_note-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>Similarly, one of the two main schools of thought in <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagoreanism" title=3D"Pythagoreanism">Pythagor=
eanism</a> was known as the <i>math=C4=93matikoi</i> (=CE=BC=CE=B1=CE=B8=CE=
=B7=CE=BC=CE=B1=CF=84=CE=B9=CE=BA=CE=BF=CE=AF)=E2=80=94which at the time me=
ant "learners" rather than "mathematicians" in the modern sense. The Pythag=
oreans were likely the first to constrain the use of the word to just the s=
tudy of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic" title=3D"Arith=
metic">arithmetic</a> and geometry. By the time of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Aristotle" title=3D"Aristotle">Aristotle</a> (384=E2=80=93=
322&nbsp;BC) this meaning was fully established.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-70" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_=
note-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In Latin and English, until around 1700, the term <i>mathematics</i>=
 more commonly meant "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astrology" t=
itle=3D"Astrology">astrology</a>" (or sometimes "<a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Astronomy" title=3D"Astronomy">astronomy</a>") rather than "=
mathematics"; the meaning gradually changed to its present one from about 1=
500 to 1800. This change has resulted in several mistranslations: For examp=
le, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Augustine" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Saint Augustine">Saint Augustine</a>'s warning that Chris=
tians should beware of <i>mathematici</i>, meaning "astrologers", is someti=
mes mistranslated as a condemnation of mathematicians.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-B=
oas_71-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Math=
ematics#cite_note-Boas-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The apparent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plural" title=
=3D"Plural">plural</a> form in English goes back to the Latin <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuter_(grammar)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Neuter (grammar)">neuter</a> plural <span title=3D"Latin-language text"=
><i lang=3D"la">mathematica</i></span> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Cicero" title=3D"Cicero">Cicero</a>), based on the Greek plural <i>ta=
 math=C4=93matik=C3=A1</i> (<span title=3D"Greek-language text"><span lang=
=3D"el">=CF=84=E1=BD=B0 =CE=BC=CE=B1=CE=B8=CE=B7=CE=BC=CE=B1=CF=84=CE=B9=CE=
=BA=CE=AC</span></span>) and means roughly "all things mathematical", altho=
ugh it is plausible that English borrowed only the adjective <i>mathematic(=
al)</i> and formed the noun <i>mathematics</i> anew, after the pattern of <=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" title=3D"Physics">physi=
cs</a></i> and <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metaphysics" tit=
le=3D"Metaphysics">metaphysics</a></i>, inherited from Greek.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-72" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Math=
ematics#cite_note-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In English, the noun <i>mathematics</i> t=
akes a singular verb. It is often shortened to <i>maths</i><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-73" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathem=
atics#cite_note-73"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or, in North America, <i>math</i>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-74" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Mathematics#cite_note-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ancient">Ancient</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Plimpton_322.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-descriptio=
n"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Pl=
impton_322.jpg/250px-Plimpton_322.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" hei=
ght=3D"173" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1246" data-file-he=
ight=3D"863"></a><figcaption>The Babylonian mathematical tablet <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plimpton_322" title=3D"Plimpton 322">Plim=
pton 322</a></i>, dated to 1800&nbsp;BC</figcaption></figure>
<p>In addition to recognizing how to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Counting" title=3D"Counting">count</a> physical objects, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prehistoric" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prehi=
storic">prehistoric</a> peoples may have also known how to count abstract q=
uantities, like time=E2=80=94days, seasons, or years.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-75=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#=
cite_note-75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-76" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-76"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>73<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Ev=
idence for more complex mathematics does not appear until around 3000&nbsp;=
<abbr title=3D"Before Christ">BC</abbr>, when the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Babylonia" title=3D"Babylonia">Babylonians</a> and Egyptian=
s began using arithmetic, algebra, and geometry for taxation and other fina=
ncial calculations, for building and construction, and for astronomy.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKline1990Chapter_1_77-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKline1990Ch=
apter_1-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>74<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> The oldest mathematical texts from <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesopotamia" title=3D"Mesopotamia">Mesopotamia</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Egypt" title=3D"Ancie=
nt Egypt">Egypt</a> are from 2000 to 1800&nbsp;BC.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-78" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cit=
e_note-78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> Many early texts mention <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_triple" title=3D"Pythagorean triple">Pythagorean =
triples</a> and so, by inference, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Pythagorean_theorem" title=3D"Pythagorean theorem">Pythagorean theorem<=
/a> seems to be the most ancient and widespread mathematical concept after =
basic arithmetic and geometry. It is in Babylonian mathematics that <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_arithmetic" title=3D"Elementar=
y arithmetic">elementary arithmetic</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Addition" title=3D"Addition">addition</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Subtraction" title=3D"Subtraction">subtraction</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplication" title=3D"Multiplication">=
multiplication</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Division_(=
mathematics)" title=3D"Division (mathematics)">division</a>) first appear i=
n the archaeological record. The Babylonians also possessed a place-value s=
ystem and used a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sexagesimal" titl=
e=3D"Sexagesimal">sexagesimal</a> numeral system which is still in use toda=
y for measuring angles and time.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBoyer1991&quot;=
Mesopotamia&quot;_pp._24=E2=80=9327_79-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBoyer1991%22Mesop=
otamia%22_pp._24%E2%80%9327-79"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>76<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 6th century BC, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gree=
k_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Greek mathematics">Greek math=
ematics</a> began to emerge as a distinct discipline and some <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greeks" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Ancient Greeks">Ancient Greeks</a> such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Pythagoreans" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pythagoreans">Pyt=
hagoreans</a> appeared to have considered it a subject in its own right.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-80" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-80"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Around 300 BC, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a> organized mat=
hematical knowledge by way of postulates and first principles, which evolve=
d into the axiomatic method that is used in mathematics today, consisting o=
f definition, axiom, theorem, and proof.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-81"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> His book, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%2=
7s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Elements</a></i>, is widely consid=
ered the most successful and influential textbook of all time.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-FOOTNOTEBoyer1991&quot;Euclid_of_Alexandria&quot;_p._119_82-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_no=
te-FOOTNOTEBoyer1991%22Euclid_of_Alexandria%22_p._119-82"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>79<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The g=
reatest mathematician of antiquity is often held to be <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> (<abbr=
 title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89287<=
/span>&nbsp;=E2=80=93 c.<span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89212 BC=
</span>) of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syracuse,_Italy" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Syracuse, Italy">Syracuse</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-FOOTNOTEBoyer1991&quot;Archimedes_of_Syracuse&quot;_p._120_83-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-F=
OOTNOTEBoyer1991%22Archimedes_of_Syracuse%22_p._120-83"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>80<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He deve=
loped formulas for calculating the surface area and volume of <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solids_of_revolution" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Solids of revolution">solids of revolution</a> and used the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_exhaustion" title=3D"Method of =
exhaustion">method of exhaustion</a> to calculate the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"Area">area</a> under the arc of a <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parabola" title=3D"Parabola">parabola</a=
> with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Series_(mathematics)" t=
itle=3D"Series (mathematics)">summation of an infinite series</a>, in a man=
ner not too dissimilar from modern calculus.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBoy=
er1991&quot;Archimedes_of_Syracuse&quot;_p._130_84-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBoyer=
1991%22Archimedes_of_Syracuse%22_p._130-84"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other notable achie=
vements of Greek mathematics are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
onic_sections" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Conic sections">conic section=
s</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apollonius_of_Perga" title=
=3D"Apollonius of Perga">Apollonius of Perga</a>, 3rd century BC),<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBoyer1991&quot;Apollonius_of_Perga&quot;_p._145_85-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#ci=
te_note-FOOTNOTEBoyer1991%22Apollonius_of_Perga%22_p._145-85"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometry" title=3D"Trigonomet=
ry">trigonometry</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hipparchus_o=
f_Nicaea" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hipparchus of Nicaea">Hipparchus o=
f Nicaea</a>, 2nd century BC),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBoyer1991&quot;Gr=
eek_Trigonometry_and_Mensuration&quot;_p._162_86-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBoyer19=
91%22Greek_Trigonometry_and_Mensuration%22_p._162-86"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>83<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the b=
eginnings of algebra (Diophantus, 3rd century AD).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTN=
OTEBoyer1991&quot;Revival_and_Decline_of_Greek_Mathematics&quot;_p._180_87-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics=
#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBoyer1991%22Revival_and_Decline_of_Greek_Mathematics%22_=
p._180-87"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>84<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bakhshali_numerals_2.jpg" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/5/58/Bakhshali_numerals_2.jpg/500px-Bakhshali_numerals_2.j=
pg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"380" height=3D"57" class=3D"mw-file-element=
" data-file-width=3D"1958" data-file-height=3D"295"></a><figcaption>The num=
erals used in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bakhshali_manusc=
ript" title=3D"Bakhshali manuscript">Bakhshali manuscript</a>, dated betwee=
n the 2nd century BC and the 2nd century AD</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindu%E2%80%93Arabic_numera=
l_system" title=3D"Hindu=E2=80=93Arabic numeral system">Hindu=E2=80=93Arabi=
c numeral system</a> and the rules for the use of its operations, in use th=
roughout the world today, evolved over the course of the first millennium A=
D in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_mathematics" title=3D"=
Indian mathematics">India</a> and were transmitted to the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_world" title=3D"Western world">Western worl=
d</a> via <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islamic_mathematics" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Islamic mathematics">Islamic mathematics</a>.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-88" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-88"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>85<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other notable developments of=
 Indian mathematics include the modern definition and approximation of <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sine" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"S=
ine">sine</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosine" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cosine">cosine</a>, and an early form of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_series" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Infinite series">infinite series</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-89" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-89=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-90" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-90"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>87<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Medieval_and_later">Medieva=
l and later</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Image-Al-Kit%C4%81b_al-mu%E1%B8%ABta%E1%B9%A3=
ar_f%C4%AB_%E1%B8%A5is%C4%81b_al-%C4%9Fabr_wa-l-muq%C4%81bala.jpg" class=3D=
"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/co=
mmons/thumb/2/23/Image-Al-Kit%C4%81b_al-mu%E1%B8%ABta%E1%B9%A3ar_f%C4%AB_%E=
1%B8%A5is%C4%81b_al-%C4%9Fabr_wa-l-muq%C4%81bala.jpg/240px-Image-Al-Kit%C4%=
81b_al-mu%E1%B8%ABta%E1%B9%A3ar_f%C4%AB_%E1%B8%A5is%C4%81b_al-%C4%9Fabr_wa-=
l-muq%C4%81bala.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"180" height=3D"285" class=
=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"240" data-file-height=3D"380"></a><=
figcaption>A page from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Khwarizm=
i" title=3D"Al-Khwarizmi">al-Khwarizmi</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Al-Jabr" title=3D"Al-Jabr">Al-Jabr</a></i></figcaption></figu=
re>
<p>During the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_Age_of_Islam"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Golden Age of Islam">Golden Age of Islam</a=
>, especially during the 9th and 10th&nbsp;centuries, mathematics saw many =
important innovations building on Greek mathematics. The most notable achie=
vement of Islamic mathematics was the development of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">algebra</a>. Other achievemen=
ts of the Islamic period include advances in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Spherical_trigonometry" title=3D"Spherical trigonometry">spheric=
al trigonometry</a> and the addition of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Decimal_point" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Decimal point">deci=
mal point</a> to the Arabic numeral system.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-91" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-=
91"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Many notable mathematicians from this period were Persian, =
such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Khwarizmi" title=3D"Al-=
Khwarizmi">Al-Khwarizmi</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omar_=
Khayyam" title=3D"Omar Khayyam">Omar Khayyam</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharaf_al-D%C4%ABn_al-%E1%B9%AC%C5%ABs%C4%AB" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Sharaf al-D=C4=ABn al-=E1=B9=AC=C5=ABs=C4=AB">Sharaf a=
l-D=C4=ABn al-=E1=B9=AC=C5=ABs=C4=AB</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-92" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-92=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> The Greek and Arabic mathematical texts were in turn translat=
ed to Latin during the Middle Ages and made available in Europe.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-93" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
athematics#cite_note-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>90<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>During the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Early_modern_per=
iod" title=3D"Early modern period">early modern period</a>, mathematics beg=
an to develop at an accelerating pace in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Western_Europe" title=3D"Western Europe">Western Europe</a>, with in=
novations that revolutionized mathematics, such as the introduction of vari=
ables and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#Symbolic_not=
ation_and_terminology">symbolic notation</a> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Fran%C3%A7ois_Vi%C3%A8te" title=3D"Fran=C3=A7ois Vi=C3=A8te">=
Fran=C3=A7ois Vi=C3=A8te</a> (1540=E2=80=931603), the introduction of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_logarithms" title=3D"History=
 of logarithms">logarithms</a> by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
John_Napier" title=3D"John Napier">John Napier</a> in 1614, which greatly s=
implified numerical calculations, especially for <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Astronomy" title=3D"Astronomy">astronomy</a> and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marine_navigation" title=3D"Marine navigation=
">marine navigation</a>, the introduction of coordinates by <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes" title=3D"Ren=C3=A9 Descartes=
">Ren=C3=A9 Descartes</a> (1596=E2=80=931650) for reducing geometry to alge=
bra, and the development of calculus by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton">Isaac Newton</a> (1643=E2=80=931=
727) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Leibniz" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gottfried Leibniz">Gottfried Leibniz</a> (1646=E2=
=80=931716). <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Euler" title=
=3D"Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a> (1707=E2=80=931783), the most notabl=
e mathematician of the 18th century, unified these innovations into a singl=
e corpus with a standardized terminology, and completed them with the disco=
very and the proof of numerous theorems.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-94" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-94"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>91<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Carl_Friedrich_Gauss_1840_by_J=
ensen.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimed=
ia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ec/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss_1840_by_Jensen.jpg=
/250px-Carl_Friedrich_Gauss_1840_by_Jensen.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"200" height=3D"255" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1639" dat=
a-file-height=3D"2088"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">Carl Friedrich Ga=
uss</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>Perhaps the foremost mathematician of the 19th century was the German ma=
thematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Gauss" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Carl Gauss">Carl Gauss</a>, who made numerous contribu=
tions to fields such as algebra, analysis, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Differential_geometry" title=3D"Differential geometry">differentia=
l geometry</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_theory" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Matrix theory">matrix theory</a>, number theory=
, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statist=
ics">statistics</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-95" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-95"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>92<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the =
early 20th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kurt_G%C3%B6de=
l" title=3D"Kurt G=C3=B6del">Kurt G=C3=B6del</a> transformed mathematics by=
 publishing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G%C3%B6del%27s_incompl=
eteness_theorems" title=3D"G=C3=B6del's incompleteness theorems">his incomp=
leteness theorems</a>, which show in part that any consistent axiomatic sys=
tem=E2=80=94if powerful enough to describe arithmetic=E2=80=94will contain =
true propositions that cannot be proved.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Raatikainen_200=
5_58-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathem=
atics#cite_note-Raatikainen_2005-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Mathematics has since been greatly extended, and there has been a fr=
uitful interaction between mathematics and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Science" title=3D"Science">science</a>, to the benefit of both. Ma=
thematical discoveries continue to be made to this very day. According to M=
ikhail B. Sevryuk, in the January&nbsp;2006 issue of the <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bulletin_of_the_American_Mathematical_Society" ti=
tle=3D"Bulletin of the American Mathematical Society">Bulletin of the Ameri=
can Mathematical Society</a></i>, "The number of papers and books included =
in the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_Reviews" ti=
tle=3D"Mathematical Reviews">Mathematical Reviews</a></i> (MR) database sin=
ce 1940 (the first year of operation of MR) is now more than 1.9&nbsp;milli=
on, and more than 75&nbsp;thousand items are added to the database each yea=
r. The overwhelming majority of works in this ocean contain new mathematica=
l theorems and their proofs."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESevryuk2006101=E2=
=80=93109_96-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Mathematics#cite_note-FOOTNOTESevryuk2006101%E2%80%93109-96"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>93<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Symbolic_notation_and_termi=
nology">Symbolic notation and terminology</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_notati=
on" title=3D"Mathematical notation">Mathematical notation</a>, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_of_mathematics" title=3D"Language of =
mathematics">Language of mathematics</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Glossary_of_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Glossar=
y of mathematics">Glossary of mathematics</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size skin-invert-image" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Sigma_summation_notation.sv=
g" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/w=
ikipedia/commons/thumb/5/53/Sigma_summation_notation.svg/250px-Sigma_summat=
ion_notation.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"171" class=
=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"350" data-file-height=3D"240"></a><=
figcaption>An explanation of the sigma (=CE=A3) <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Summation" title=3D"Summation">summation</a> notation</figcap=
tion></figure>
<p>Mathematical notation is widely used in science and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering" title=3D"Engineering">engineering</a> for=
 representing complex <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concept" tit=
le=3D"Concept">concepts</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pr=
operty_(philosophy)" title=3D"Property (philosophy)">properties</a> in a co=
ncise, unambiguous, and accurate way. This notation consists of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glossary_of_mathematical_symbols" title=3D"Gl=
ossary of mathematical symbols">symbols</a> used for representing <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_(mathematics)" title=3D"Operati=
on (mathematics)">operations</a>, unspecified numbers, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relation_(mathematics)" title=3D"Relation (mathematics=
)">relations</a> and any other mathematical objects, and then assembling th=
em into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expression_(mathematics)" =
title=3D"Expression (mathematics)">expressions</a> and formulas.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-97" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
athematics#cite_note-97"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>94<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> More precisely, numbers and other math=
ematical objects are represented by symbols called variables, which are gen=
erally <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_alphabet" title=3D"La=
tin alphabet">Latin</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_a=
lphabet" title=3D"Greek alphabet">Greek</a> letters, and often include <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subscript" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Subscript">subscripts</a>. Operation and relations are generally repres=
ented by specific <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glossary_of_math=
ematical_symbols" title=3D"Glossary of mathematical symbols">symbols</a> or=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glyph" title=3D"Glyph">glyphs</a>=
,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-98" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-98"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9=
5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> such as <span class=3D"tex=
html">+</span> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plus_sign" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plus sign">plus</a>), <span class=3D"texhtml">=C3=
=97</span> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplication_sign" t=
itle=3D"Multiplication sign">multiplication</a>), <span class=3D"mwe-math-e=
lement mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-m=
ath-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/=
