">=3D</span> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equals_sign" title=
=3D"Equals sign">equal</a>), and <span class=3D"texhtml">&lt;</span> (<a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Less-than_sign" title=3D"Less-than sign=
">less than</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-AMS_99-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-AMS-99"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 All these symbols are generally grouped according to specific rules to for=
m expressions and formulas.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-100" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-100"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>97<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Normally, expressions and formulas do not appear alone, but are included =
in sentences of the current language, where expressions play the role of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noun_phrase" title=3D"Noun phrase">n=
oun phrases</a> and formulas play the role of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Clause" title=3D"Clause">clauses</a>.
</p><p>Mathematics has developed a rich terminology covering a broad range =
of fields that study the properties of various abstract, idealized objects =
and how they interact. It is based on rigorous <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Technical_definition" title=3D"Technical definition">definitio=
ns</a> that provide a standard foundation for communication. An axiom or <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Postulate" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Postulate">postulate</a> is a mathematical statement that is taken to=
 be true without need of proof. If a mathematical statement has yet to be p=
roven (or disproven), it is termed a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Conjecture" title=3D"Conjecture">conjecture</a>. Through a series of rig=
orous arguments employing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deductiv=
e_reasoning" title=3D"Deductive reasoning">deductive reasoning</a>, a state=
ment that is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formal_proof" title=
=3D"Formal proof">proven</a> to be true becomes a theorem. A specialized th=
eorem that is mainly used to prove another theorem is called a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lemma_(mathematics)" title=3D"Lemma (mathemati=
cs)">lemma</a>. A proven instance that forms part of a more general finding=
 is termed a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corollary" title=3D"C=
orollary">corollary</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-101" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-101"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>98<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Numerous technical terms used in mathematics are <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neologism" title=3D"Neologism">neologisms</a>, such a=
s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomi=
al">polynomial</a></i> and <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Home=
omorphism" title=3D"Homeomorphism">homeomorphism</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-102" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathema=
tics#cite_note-102"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>99<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other technical terms are words of the comm=
on language that are used in an accurate meaning that may differ slightly f=
rom their common meaning. For example, in mathematics, "<a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logical_disjunction" title=3D"Logical disjunction">or=
</a>" means "one, the other or both", while, in common language, it is eith=
er ambiguous or means "one or the other but not both" (in mathematics, the =
latter is called "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exclusive_or" ti=
tle=3D"Exclusive or">exclusive or</a>"). Finally, many mathematical terms a=
re common words that are used with a completely different meaning.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-103" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics#cite_note-103"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>100<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This may lead to sentences that=
 are correct and true mathematical assertions, but appear to be nonsense to=
 people who do not have the required background. For example, "every <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_module" title=3D"Free module">free =
module</a> is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flat_module" title=
=3D"Flat module">flat</a>" and "a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Field_(mathematics)" title=3D"Field (mathematics)">field</a> is always a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_(mathematics)" title=3D"Ring (m=
athematics)">ring</a>".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Relationship_with_sciences"=
>Relationship with sciences</h2></div>
<p>Mathematics is used in most <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sci=
ence" title=3D"Science">sciences</a> for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Mathematical_model" title=3D"Mathematical model">modeling</a> phenom=
ena, which then allows predictions to be made from experimental laws.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-104" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-104"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>101<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The independence of mathematic=
al truth from any experimentation implies that the accuracy of such predict=
ions depends only on the adequacy of the model.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-105" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_=
note-105"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>102<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> Inaccurate predictions, rather than being caused by =
invalid mathematical concepts, imply the need to change the mathematical mo=
del used.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-106" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-106"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>103<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perihelion_precession_of_Mercury=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Perihelion precession of Mercury">periheli=
on precession of Mercury</a> could only be explained after the emergence of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Einstein" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Einstein">Einstein</a>'s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
eneral_relativity" title=3D"General relativity">general relativity</a>, whi=
ch replaced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton%27s_law_of_grav=
itation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Newton's law of gravitation">Newton=
's law of gravitation</a> as a better mathematical model.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-107" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathema=
tics#cite_note-107"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>104<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>There is still a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy=
_of_mathematics" title=3D"Philosophy of mathematics">philosophical</a> deba=
te whether mathematics is a science. However, in practice, mathematicians a=
re typically grouped with scientists, and mathematics shares much in common=
 with the physical sciences. Like them, it is <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Falsifiable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Falsifiable">falsif=
iable</a>, which means in mathematics that, if a result or a theory is wron=
g, this can be proved by providing a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Counterexample" title=3D"Counterexample">counterexample</a>. Similarly a=
s in science, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_theory"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematical theory">theories</a> and resul=
ts (theorems) are often obtained from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Experimentation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Experimentation">experi=
mentation</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-108" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-108"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>105<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In mathema=
tics, the experimentation may consist of computation on selected examples o=
r of the study of figures or other representations of mathematical objects =
(often mind representations without physical support). For example, when as=
ked how he came about his theorems, Gauss once replied "durch planm=C3=A4ss=
iges Tattonieren" (through systematic experimentation).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
109" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathemati=
cs#cite_note-109"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>106<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, some authors emphasize that mathema=
tics differs from the modern notion of science by not <em>relying</em> on e=
mpirical evidence.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bishop1991_110-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Bishop1991-=
110"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>107<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-111" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-111"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>108<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Nickles2013_112-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Nickles2013-112"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>109<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Pigliucci2014_113-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Pigliucci2014-113"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>110<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Pure_and_applied_mathematic=
s">Pure and applied mathematics</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Applied_mathematics=
" title=3D"Applied mathematics">Applied mathematics</a> and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pure_mathematics" title=3D"Pure mathematics">Pure=
 mathematics</a></div>
<div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><div class=3D"thumbinner multiimageinner=
" style=3D"width:322px;max-width:322px"><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"t=
single" style=3D"width:150px;max-width:150px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" sty=
le=3D"height:202px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:GodfreyKneller-IsaacNewton-1689.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"Isaac Newton" src=3D"https://upload.wi=
kimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/GodfreyKneller-IsaacNewton-1689.jp=
g/250px-GodfreyKneller-IsaacNewton-1689.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"14=
8" height=3D"208" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1364" data-f=
ile-height=3D"1916"></a></span></div></div><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"=
width:168px;max-width:168px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:202p=
x;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/File:Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz,_Bernhard_Christoph_Francke.jpg" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"Gottfried Wilhelm von Leibniz" src=
=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Gottfried_Wil=
helm_Leibniz%2C_Bernhard_Christoph_Francke.jpg/250px-Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leib=
niz%2C_Bernhard_Christoph_Francke.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"166" hei=
ght=3D"205" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4486" data-file-he=
ight=3D"5538"></a></span></div></div></div><div class=3D"trow" style=3D"dis=
play:flex"><div class=3D"thumbcaption">Isaac Newton (left) and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz" title=3D"Gottfried =
Wilhelm Leibniz">Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz</a> developed infinitesimal calc=
ulus.</div></div></div></div>
<p>Until the 19th century, the development of mathematics in the West was m=
ainly motivated by the needs of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Te=
chnology" title=3D"Technology">technology</a> and science, and there was no=
 clear distinction between pure and applied mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Ferreir=C3=B3s_2007_114-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Ferreir%C3%B3s_2007-114"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>111<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> F=
or example, the natural numbers and arithmetic were introduced for the need=
 of counting, and geometry was motivated by surveying, architecture, and as=
tronomy. Later, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton" titl=
e=3D"Isaac Newton">Isaac Newton</a> introduced infinitesimal calculus for e=
xplaining the movement of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plan=
et" title=3D"Planet">planets</a> with his law of gravitation. Moreover, mos=
t mathematicians were also scientists, and many scientists were also mathem=
aticians.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-115" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-115"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>112<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, a nota=
ble exception occurred with the tradition of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Pure_mathematics_in_Ancient_Greece" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Pure mathematics in Ancient Greece">pure mathematics in Ancient Greece<=
/a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-116" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-116"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>113<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The problem of <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_factorization" title=3D"Integer=
 factorization">integer factorization</a>, for example, which goes back to =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a=
> in 300 BC, had no practical application before its use in the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem" title=3D"RSA cryptosystem">=
RSA cryptosystem</a>, now widely used for the security of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_network" title=3D"Computer network">comput=
er networks</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-117" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-117"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>114<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 19th century, mathematicians such as <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Weierstrass" title=3D"Karl Weierstrass">Karl Weierstr=
ass</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Dedekind" titl=
e=3D"Richard Dedekind">Richard Dedekind</a> increasingly focused their rese=
arch on internal problems, that is, <i>pure mathematics</i>.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Ferreir=C3=B3s_2007_114-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Ferreir%C3%B3s_2007-114"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>111<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p><sup id=3D"cite_ref-118" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-118"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>115<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This led to split math=
ematics into <i>pure mathematics</i> and <i>applied mathematics</i>, the la=
tter being often considered as having a lower value among mathematical puri=
sts. However, the lines between the two are frequently blurred.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-119" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
athematics#cite_note-119"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>116<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The aftermath of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_=
II" title=3D"World War II">World War II</a> led to a surge in the developme=
nt of applied mathematics in the US and elsewhere.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-120" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#ci=
te_note-120"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>117<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-121" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-121"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>118<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Many of the theories developed for applications were found interesting fr=
om the point of view of pure mathematics, and many results of pure mathemat=
ics were shown to have applications outside mathematics; in turn, the study=
 of these applications may give new insights on the "pure theory".<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-122" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics#cite_note-122"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>119<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-123" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_no=
te-123"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>120<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>An example of the first case is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Theory_of_distributions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Theory of =
distributions">theory of distributions</a>, introduced by <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laurent_Schwartz" title=3D"Laurent Schwartz">Lauren=
t Schwartz</a> for validating computations done in <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_mechanics" title=3D"Quantum mechanics">quantum mec=
hanics</a>, which became immediately an important tool of (pure) mathematic=
al analysis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-124" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-124"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>121<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An example o=
f the second case is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decidabil=
ity_of_the_first-order_theory_of_the_real_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Decidability of the first-order theory of the real numbers">decidabi=
lity of the first-order theory of the real numbers</a>, a problem of pure m=
athematics that was proved true by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Alfred_Tarski" title=3D"Alfred Tarski">Alfred Tarski</a>, with an algorith=
m that is impossible to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Implementa=
tion_(computer_science)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Implementation (com=
puter science)">implement</a> because of a computational complexity that is=
 much too high.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-125" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-125"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>122<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For getti=
ng an algorithm that can be implemented and can solve systems of polynomial=
 equations and inequalities, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georg=
e_E._Collins" title=3D"George E. Collins">George Collins</a> introduced the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylindrical_algebraic_decompositi=
on" title=3D"Cylindrical algebraic decomposition">cylindrical algebraic dec=
omposition</a> that became a fundamental tool in <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Real_algebraic_geometry" title=3D"Real algebraic geometry">r=
eal algebraic geometry</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-126" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-126"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>123<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p>In the present day, the distinction between pure and applied mathema=
tics is more a question of personal research aim of mathematicians than a d=
ivision of mathematics into broad areas.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-127" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-12=
7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>124<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-128" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-128"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>125<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Mathe=
matics Subject Classification has a section for "general applied mathematic=
s" but does not mention "pure mathematics".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MSC_8-9" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_=
note-MSC-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> However, these terms are still used in names of some=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University" title=3D"University">=
university</a> departments, such as at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Faculty_of_Mathematics,_University_of_Cambridge" title=3D"Faculty =
of Mathematics, University of Cambridge">Faculty of Mathematics</a> at the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Cambridge" title=3D"=
University of Cambridge">University of Cambridge</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Unreasonable_effectiveness"=
>Unreasonable effectiveness</h3></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unreasonable_effectiveness_=
of_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Unreasonable effectiveness o=
f mathematics">unreasonable effectiveness of mathematics</a> is a phenomeno=
n that was named and first made explicit by physicist <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugene_Wigner" title=3D"Eugene Wigner">Eugene Wigner</a=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-wigner1960_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-wigner1960-3"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It i=
s the fact that many mathematical theories (even the "purest") have applica=
tions outside their initial object. These applications may be completely ou=
tside their initial area of mathematics, and may concern physical phenomena=
 that were completely unknown when the mathematical theory was introduced.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-129" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-129"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Examples of unexpected ap=
plications of mathematical theories can be found in many areas of mathemati=
cs.
</p><p>A notable example is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pr=
ime_factorization" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prime factorization">prim=
e factorization</a> of natural numbers that was discovered more than 2,000 =
years before its common use for secure <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Internet" title=3D"Internet">internet</a> communications through the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_cryptosystem" title=3D"RSA cryp=
tosystem">RSA cryptosystem</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-130" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-130"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>127<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> A second historical example is the theory of <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipse" title=3D"Ellipse">ellipses</a>. They were studie=
d by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Greek_mathematici=
ans" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ancient Greek mathematicians">ancient G=
reek mathematicians</a> as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conic_s=
ection" title=3D"Conic section">conic sections</a> (that is, intersections =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cone" title=3D"Cone">cones</a> =
with planes). It was almost 2,000 years later that <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_Kepler" title=3D"Johannes Kepler">Johannes Kepler=
</a> discovered that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trajector=
ies" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Trajectories">trajectories</a> of the p=
lanets are ellipses.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-131" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-131"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>128<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the 19th century, the internal development of geometry (pure math=
ematics) led to definition and study of non-Euclidean geometries, spaces of=
 dimension higher than three and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
anifold" title=3D"Manifold">manifolds</a>. At this time, these concepts see=
med totally disconnected from the physical reality, but at the beginning of=
 the 20th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein=
" title=3D"Albert Einstein">Albert Einstein</a> developed the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theory_of_relativity" title=3D"Theory of relati=
vity">theory of relativity</a> that uses fundamentally these concepts. In p=
articular, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spacetime" title=3D"Spa=
cetime">spacetime</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special_r=
elativity" title=3D"Special relativity">special relativity</a> is a non-Euc=
lidean space of dimension four, and spacetime of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/General_relativity" title=3D"General relativity">general rel=
ativity</a> is a (curved) manifold of dimension four.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13=
2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics=
#cite_note-132"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>129<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-133" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-133"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>130<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>A striking aspect of the interaction between mathematics and physics=
 is when mathematics drives research in physics. This is illustrated by the=
 discoveries of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positron" titl=
e=3D"Positron">positron</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Omega_baryon" title=3D"Omega baryon">baryon</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-e=
lement mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-m=
ath-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/=
1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \Omega ^{-}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
