wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Supply-demand-equilibrium.svg/250px-Supply-dem=
and-equilibrium.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" cl=
ass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"217" data-file-height=3D"217"></=
a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supply_and_demand" t=
itle=3D"Supply and demand">Supply and demand</a> curves, like this one, are=
 a staple of mathematical economics.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Often the fundamental postulate of mathematical economics is that of the=
 rational individual actor =E2=80=93 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Homo_economicus" title=3D"Homo economicus">Homo economicus</a></i> (<=
abbr style=3D"font-size:85%" title=3D"literal translation">lit.</abbr><span=
 style=3D"white-space: nowrap;">=E2=80=89</span><span class=3D"gloss-quot">=
'</span><span class=3D"gloss-text">economic man</span><span class=3D"gloss-=
quot">'</span>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_156-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-:3-156"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>153<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> In this model, the individual seeks to maximize their <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_choice_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Rational choice theory">self-interest</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_156-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#c=
ite_note-:3-156"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>153<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and always makes optimal choices using <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_information" title=3D"Perfect in=
formation">perfect information</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-157" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-157"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>154<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> This atomistic view of economics allows it to relatively easily =
mathematize its thinking, because individual <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Calculations" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Calculations">calcu=
lations</a> are transposed into mathematical calculations. Such mathematica=
l modeling allows one to probe economic mechanisms. Some reject or criticis=
e the concept of <i>Homo economicus</i>. Economists note that real people h=
ave limited information, make poor choices, and care about fairness and alt=
ruism, not just personal gain.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-158" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-158"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>155<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>Without mathematical modeling, it is hard to go beyond statistical o=
bservations or untestable speculation. Mathematical modeling allows economi=
sts to create structured frameworks to test hypotheses and analyze complex =
interactions. Models provide clarity and precision, enabling the translatio=
n of theoretical concepts into quantifiable predictions that can be tested =
against real-world data.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-159" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-159"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>156<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>At the start of the 20th century, there was a development to express=
 historical movements in formulas. In 1922, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Nikolai_Kondratiev" title=3D"Nikolai Kondratiev">Nikolai Kondrati=
ev</a> discerned the ~50-year-long <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Kondratiev_cycle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kondratiev cycle">Kondrat=
iev cycle</a>, which explains phases of economic growth or crisis.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-160" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics#cite_note-160"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>157<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Towards the end of the 19th cen=
tury, mathematicians extended their analysis into <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Geopolitics" title=3D"Geopolitics">geopolitics</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-161" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics#cite_note-161"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>158<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Peter_Turchin" title=3D"Peter Turchin">Peter Turchin</a> develope=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cliodynamics" title=3D"Cliodynam=
ics">cliodynamics</a> in the 1990s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-162" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-162"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>159<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>
</p><p>Mathematization of the social sciences is not without risk. In the c=
ontroversial book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fashionable_N=
onsense" title=3D"Fashionable Nonsense">Fashionable Nonsense</a></i> (1997)=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Sokal" title=3D"Alan Sokal"=
>Sokal</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_Bricmont" titl=
e=3D"Jean Bricmont">Bricmont</a> denounced the unfounded or abusive use of =
scientific terminology, particularly from mathematics or physics, in the so=
cial sciences.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-163" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-163"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>160<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The study =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_systems" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Complex systems">complex systems</a> (evolution of unemplo=
yment, business capital, demographic evolution of a population, etc.) uses =
mathematical knowledge. However, the choice of counting criteria, particula=
rly for unemployment, or of models, can be subject to controversy.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-164" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics#cite_note-164"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>161<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-165" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_no=
te-165"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>162<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Philosophy">Philosophy</h2>=
</div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy_of_mathem=
atics" title=3D"Philosophy of mathematics">Philosophy of mathematics</a></d=
iv>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Reality">Reality</h3></div>
<p>The connection between mathematics and material reality has led to philo=
sophical debates since at least the time of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Pythagoras" title=3D"Pythagoras">Pythagoras</a>. The ancient phil=
osopher <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plato" title=3D"Plato">Pla=
to</a> argued that abstractions that reflect material reality have themselv=
es a reality that exists outside space and time. As a result, the philosoph=
ical view that mathematical objects somehow exist on their own in abstracti=
on is often referred to as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathema=
tical_Platonism" title=3D"Mathematical Platonism">Platonism</a>. Independen=
tly of their possible philosophical opinions, modern mathematicians may be =
generally considered as Platonists, since they think of and talk of their o=
bjects of study as real objects.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SEP-Platonism_166-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite=
_note-SEP-Platonism-166"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>163<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armand_Borel" title=3D"Arma=
nd Borel">Armand Borel</a> summarized this view of mathematics reality as f=
ollows, and provided quotations of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/G._H._Hardy" title=3D"G. H. Hardy">G. H. Hardy</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Hermite" title=3D"Charles Hermite">Charles Hermi=
te</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Poincar%C3%A9" title=
=3D"Henri Poincar=C3=A9">Henri Poincar=C3=A9</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein" title=3D"Albert Einstein">Albert Einste=
in</a> that support his views.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-borel_134-1" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-bore=
l-134"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>131<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p> Something becomes objective (as opp=
osed to "subjective") as soon as we are convinced that it exists in the min=
ds of others in the same form as it does in ours and that we can think abou=
t it and discuss it together.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-167" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-167"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>164<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> Because the language of mathematics is so precise, it is ideally suite=
d to defining concepts for which such a consensus exists. In my opinion, th=
at is sufficient to provide us with a <em>feeling</em> of an objective exis=
tence, of a reality of mathematics ...</p></blockquote>
<p>Nevertheless, Platonism and the concurrent views on abstraction do not e=
xplain the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#Unreasonabl=
e_effectiveness">unreasonable effectiveness</a> of mathematics (as Platonis=
m assumes mathematics exists independently, but does not explain why it mat=
ches reality).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-168" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-168"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>165<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proposed_definitions">Propo=
sed definitions</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Definitions_of_mathe=
matics" title=3D"Definitions of mathematics">Definitions of mathematics</a>=
</div>
<p>There is no general consensus about the definition of mathematics or its=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epistemology" title=3D"Epistemolo=
gy">epistemological status</a>=E2=80=94that is, its place inside knowledge.=
 A great many professional mathematicians take no interest in a definition =
of mathematics, or consider it undefinable. There is not even consensus on =
whether mathematics is an art or a science. Some just say, "mathematics is =
what mathematicians do".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mura_169-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Mura-169"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>166<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Runge_170-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Runge-170"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>167<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> A common approach is to define mathematics by its object of study.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-171" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Mathematics#cite_note-171"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>168<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMura=
1993379,_381_172-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMura1993379,_381-172"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>169<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBrownPorter1995326_173-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBrownPorte=
r1995326-173"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>170<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-174" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-174"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>171<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>Aristotle defined mathematics as "the science of quantity" and this =
definition prevailed until the 18th century. However, Aristotle also noted =
a focus on quantity alone may not distinguish mathematics from sciences lik=
e physics; in his view, abstraction and studying quantity as a property "se=
parable in thought" from real instances set mathematics apart.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Franklin_175-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Franklin-175"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>172<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the 19th centu=
ry, when mathematicians began to address topics=E2=80=94such as infinite se=
ts=E2=80=94which have no clear-cut relation to physical reality, a variety =
of new definitions were given.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cajori_176-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Caj=
ori-176"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>173<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> With the large number of new areas of mathematics tha=
t have appeared since the beginning of the 20th century, defining mathemati=
cs by its object of study has become increasingly difficult.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-FOOTNOTEDevlin2018[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidgUb7CAAAQBAJpgPA3_3]_177-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics=
#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDevlin2018[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidgUb7CAAAQBAJpgPA3_3=
]-177"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>174<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> For example, in lieu of a definition, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saunders_Mac_Lane" title=3D"Saunders Mac Lane">Saun=
ders Mac Lane</a> in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematic=
s,_form_and_function" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematics, form and =
function">Mathematics, form and function</a></i> summarizes the basics of s=
everal areas of mathematics, emphasizing their inter-connectedness, and obs=
erves:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-178" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-178"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>175<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>the development of Mathe=
matics provides a tightly connected network of formal rules, concepts, and =
systems.  Nodes of this network are closely bound to procedures useful in h=
uman activities and to questions arising in science. The transition from ac=
tivities to the formal Mathematical systems is guided by a variety of gener=
al insights and ideas.</p></blockquote>
<p>Another approach for defining mathematics is to use its methods. For exa=
mple, an area of study is often qualified as mathematics as soon as one can=
 prove theorems=E2=80=94assertions whose validity relies on a proof, that i=
s, a purely logical deduction.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-179" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-179"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>d<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-180" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-180"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>176<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"noprint =
Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability" title=3D"Wikipedia:Verifiability"=
><span title=3D"The material near this tag failed verification of its sourc=
e citation(s). (October 2024)">failed verification</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rigor">Rigor</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logic" title=3D"Logic">L=
ogic</a></div>
<p>Mathematical reasoning requires <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Mathematical_rigor" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematical rigor">rig=
or</a>. This means that the definitions must be absolutely unambiguous and =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proof_(mathematics)" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Proof (mathematics)">proofs</a> must be reducible to =
a succession of applications of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
ference_rule" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inference rule">inference rule=
s</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-181" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-181"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>e<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> without any use of e=
mpirical evidence and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intuition" t=
itle=3D"Intuition">intuition</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-182" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-182"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>f<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-183" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-183"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>177<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Rigorous reasoning=
 is not specific to mathematics, but, in mathematics, the standard of rigor=
 is much higher than elsewhere. Despite mathematics' <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Concision" title=3D"Concision">concision</a>, rigorous p=
roofs can require hundreds of pages to express, such as the 255-page <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feit%E2%80%93Thompson_theorem" title=3D"=
Feit=E2=80=93Thompson theorem">Feit=E2=80=93Thompson theorem</a>.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-184" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Mathematics#cite_note-184"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>g<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The emergence of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer-assisted_proof" title=3D"Computer-assisted p=
roof">computer-assisted proofs</a> has allowed proof lengths to further exp=
and.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-185" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-185"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>h<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-186=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#=
cite_note-186"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>178<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>  The result of this trend is a philosophy of th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasi-empiricism_in_mathematics"=
 title=3D"Quasi-empiricism in mathematics">quasi-empiricist</a> proof that =
can not be considered infallible, but has a probability attached to it.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Kleiner_1991_7-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Kleiner_1991-7"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The concept of rigor in mathematics dates back to ancient Greece, wh=
ere their society encouraged logical, deductive reasoning. However, this ri=
gorous approach would tend to discourage exploration of new approaches, suc=
h as irrational numbers and concepts of infinity. The method of demonstrati=
ng rigorous proof was enhanced in the sixteenth century through the use of =
symbolic notation. In the 18th century, social transition led to mathematic=
ians earning their keep through teaching, which led to more careful thinkin=
g about the underlying concepts of mathematics. This produced more rigorous=
 approaches, while transitioning from geometric methods to algebraic and th=
en arithmetic proofs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kleiner_1991_7-4" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Kleiner_=
1991-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>At the end of the 19th century, it appeared that the definitions of =
the basic concepts of mathematics were not accurate enough for avoiding par=
adoxes (non-Euclidean geometries and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Weierstrass_function" title=3D"Weierstrass function">Weierstrass functio=
n</a>) and contradictions (Russell's paradox). This was solved by the inclu=
sion of axioms with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apodictic"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Apodictic">apodictic</a> inference rules of=
 mathematical theories; the re-introduction of axiomatic method pioneered b=
y the ancient Greeks.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kleiner_1991_7-5" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-Kleiner_=
1991-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> It results that "rigor" is no more a relevant concept in=
 mathematics, as a proof is either correct or erroneous, and a "rigorous pr=
oof" is simply a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pleonasm" title=
=3D"Pleonasm">pleonasm</a>. Where a special concept of rigor comes into pla=
y is in the socialized aspects of a proof, wherein it may be demonstrably r=
efuted by other mathematicians. After a proof has been accepted for many ye=
ars or even decades, it can then be considered as reliable.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-187" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathe=
matics#cite_note-187"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>179<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Nevertheless, the concept of "rigor" may remain useful for teaching =
to beginners what is a mathematical proof.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-188" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-=
188"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>180<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Training_and_practice">Trai=
ning and practice</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Education">Education</h3></=
div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_educatio=
n" title=3D"Mathematics education">Mathematics education</a></div>
<p>Mathematics has a remarkable ability to cross cultural boundaries and ti=
me periods. As a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_activity" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Human activity">human activity</a>, the pract=
ice of mathematics has a social side, which includes <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_education" title=3D"Mathematics education">e=
ducation</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematician" title=
=3D"Mathematician">careers</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Li=
st_of_mathematics_awards" title=3D"List of mathematics awards">recognition<=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Popular_mathematics" title=3D=
"Popular mathematics">popularization</a>, and so on. In education, mathemat=
ics is a core part of the curriculum and forms an important element of the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/STEM" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"STEM">STEM</a> academic disciplines. Prominent careers for professional=
 mathematicians include mathematics teacher or professor, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistician" title=3D"Statistician">statistician</=
a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Actuary" title=3D"Actuary">act=
uary</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_analyst" title=
=3D"Financial analyst">financial analyst</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Economist" title=3D"Economist">economist</a>, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accountant" title=3D"Accountant">accountant</a>, <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodity_trader" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Commodity trader">commodity trader</a>, or <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_technology_consulting" title=3D"Informati=
on technology consulting">computer consultant</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-189" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#ci=
te_note-189"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>181<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Archaeological evidence shows that instruction in mathematics occurr=
ed as early as the second millennium BCE in ancient Babylonia.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-190" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
thematics#cite_note-190"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>182<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Comparable evidence has been unearthe=
d for scribal mathematics training in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Ancient_Near_East" title=3D"Ancient Near East">ancient Near East</a=
> and then for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greco-Roman_wor=
ld" title=3D"Greco-Roman world">Greco-Roman world</a> starting around 300 B=
CE.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-191" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-191"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>183<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The oldest known math=
ematics textbook is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhind_papy=
rus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Rhind papyrus">Rhind papyrus</a>, dated=
 from <abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=
=E2=80=891650 BCE</span> in Egypt.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-192" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-192"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>184<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> Due to a scarcity of books, mathematical teachings in ancient Ind=
ia were communicated using memorized <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Oral_tradition" title=3D"Oral tradition">oral tradition</a> since the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vedic_period" title=3D"Vedic period"=
>Vedic period</a> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-spac=
e:nowrap;">=E2=80=891500</span>&nbsp;=E2=80=93 c.<span style=3D"white-space=
:nowrap;">=E2=80=89500 BCE</span>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-193" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-193"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>185<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_China" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Imperial China">Imperial China</a> during the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tang_dynasty" title=3D"Tang dynasty"=
>Tang dynasty</a> (618=E2=80=93907 CE), a mathematics curriculum was adopte=
d for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_examination" ti=
tle=3D"Imperial examination">civil service exam</a> to join the state burea=
ucracy.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-194" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-194"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>186<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Following the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark_Age" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dark Age">Dark Ages</a>, mathematics education =
in Europe was provided by religious schools as part of the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrivium" title=3D"Quadrivium">Quadrivium</a>. F=
ormal instruction in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedagogy" tit=
le=3D"Pedagogy">pedagogy</a> began with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Jesuit" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Jesuit">Jesuit</a> schools in =
the 16th and 17th century. Most mathematical curricula remained at a basic =
and practical level until the nineteenth century, when it began to flourish=
 in France and Germany. The oldest journal addressing instruction in mathem=
atics was <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%27Enseignement_Math=
%C3%A9matique" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"L'Enseignement Math=C3=A9mati=
que">L'Enseignement Math=C3=A9matique</a></i>, which began publication in 1=
899.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-195" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-195"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>187<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The Western advancem=
ents in science and technology led to the establishment of centralized educ=
ation systems in many nation-states, with mathematics as a core component=
=E2=80=94initially for its military applications.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-196" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cit=
e_note-196"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>188<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> While the content of courses varies, in the presen=
t day nearly all countries teach mathematics to students for significant am=
ounts of time.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-197" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-197"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>189<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>During school, mathematical capabilities and positive expectations h=
ave a strong association with career interest in the field. Extrinsic facto=
rs such as feedback motivation by teachers, parents, and peer groups can in=
fluence the level of interest in mathematics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-198" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_no=
te-198"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>190<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> Some students studying mathematics may develop an appr=
ehension or fear about their performance in the subject. This is known as <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_anxiety" title=3D"Math=
ematical anxiety">mathematical anxiety</a>, and is considered the most prom=
inent of the disorders impacting academic performance. Mathematical anxiety=
 can develop due to various factors such as parental and teacher attitudes,=
 social stereotypes, and personal traits. Help to counteract the anxiety ca=
n come from changes in instructional approaches, by interactions with paren=
ts and teachers, and by tailored treatments for the individual.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-199" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
athematics#cite_note-199"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>191<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Psychology_(aesthetic,_crea=
tivity_and_intuition)"><span id=3D"Psychology_.28aesthetic.2C_creativity_an=
d_intuition.29"></span>Psychology (aesthetic, creativity and intuition)</h3=
></div>
<p>The validity of a mathematical theorem relies only on the rigor of its p=
roof, which could theoretically be done automatically by a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_program" title=3D"Computer program">compu=
ter program</a>. This does not mean that there is no place for creativity i=
n a mathematical work. On the contrary, many important mathematical results=
 (theorems) are solutions of problems that other mathematicians failed to s=
olve, and the invention of a way for solving them may be a fundamental way =
of the solving process.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-200" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-200"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>192<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-201" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-201"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19=
3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An extreme example is <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apery%27s_theorem" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Apery's theorem">Apery's theorem</a>: <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Apery" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Roger Apery">Ro=
ger Apery</a> provided only the ideas for a proof, and the formal proof was=
 given only several months later by three other mathematicians.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-202" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
athematics#cite_note-202"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>194<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Creativity and rigor are not the only psychological aspects of the a=
ctivity of mathematicians. Some mathematicians can see their activity as a =
game, more specifically as solving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Puzzle" title=3D"Puzzle">puzzles</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-203" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-203"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>195<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> This aspect of mathematical activity is emphasized in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recreational_mathematics" title=3D"Recrea=
tional mathematics">recreational mathematics</a>.
</p><p>Mathematicians can find an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Aesthetic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Aesthetic">aesthetic</a> value to=
 mathematics. Like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beauty" title=
=3D"Beauty">beauty</a>, it is hard to define, it is commonly related to <i>=
elegance</i>, which involves qualities like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Simplicity" title=3D"Simplicity">simplicity</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetry" title=3D"Symmetry">symmetry</a>, complet=
eness, and generality. G. H. Hardy in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/A_Mathematician%27s_Apology" title=3D"A Mathematician's Apology">A M=
athematician's Apology</a></i> expressed the belief that the aesthetic cons=
iderations are, in themselves, sufficient to justify the study of pure math=
ematics. He also identified other criteria such as significance, unexpected=
ness, and inevitability, which contribute to mathematical aesthetics.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-204" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-204"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>196<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Paul_Erd%C5%91s" title=3D"Paul Erd=C5=91s">Paul Erd=C5=91s</a> e=
xpressed this sentiment more ironically by speaking of "The Book", a suppos=
ed divine collection of the most beautiful proofs. The 1998 book <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proofs_from_THE_BOOK" title=3D"Proofs fro=
m THE BOOK">Proofs from THE BOOK</a></i>, inspired by Erd=C5=91s, is a coll=
ection of particularly succinct and revelatory mathematical arguments. Some=
 examples of particularly elegant results included are Euclid's proof that =
there are infinitely many prime numbers and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Fast_Fourier_transform" title=3D"Fast Fourier transform">fast=
 Fourier transform</a> for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harmoni=
c_analysis" title=3D"Harmonic analysis">harmonic analysis</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-205" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
thematics#cite_note-205"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>197<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some feel that to consider mathematics a science is to downplay its =
artistry and history in the seven traditional <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Liberal_arts" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Liberal arts">libe=
ral arts</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-206" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-206"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>198<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> One way thi=
s difference of viewpoint plays out is in the philosophical debate as to wh=
ether mathematical results are <i>created</i> (as in art) or <i>discovered<=
/i> (as in science).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-borel_134-2" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics#cite_note-borel-134"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>131<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> The popularity of recreational mathematics is another sign of the=
 pleasure many find in solving mathematical questions.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Cultural_impact">Cultural i=
mpact</h2></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Artistic_expression">Artist=
ic expression</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_and_art"=
 title=3D"Mathematics and art">Mathematics and art</a></div>
<p>Notes that sound well together to a Western ear are sounds whose fundame=
ntal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequencies" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Frequencies">frequencies</a> of vibration are in simple rati=
os. For example, an octave doubles the frequency and a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perfect_fifth" title=3D"Perfect fifth">perfect fifth</=
a> multiplies it by <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline=
"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"disp=
lay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{=
